Hurricane Floyd's peril for residents of the Bahamas and the U.S. Southeast coast
    happens to be a bonanza for the Weather Channel's

. News and information about the storm is a big draw. Weather Channel president
    Debora Wilson told CBS.MarketWatch.com that her Web site delivered 15 million page
    views on Monday, five times the site's daily average. "And today, we know we will
    significantly exceed that record." Wilson said her operation prepared for the
    expected rush of visitors. "We went into severe-weather mode to keep the site
    accessible to as many people as possible," she said. That means reducing graphics and
    colors on the pages to "skinny down" the site. "If we're able to do that --

Headlines.Headline: E-tailer goes where few have gone before - 04-17-98

#text: The week-old e-commerce site, Priceline.com (

), is reporting hefty traffic from
    bargain hunting travel shoppers, but it's spending very hefty dollars to attract them. The
    "name your price" venture's 60-day promotional launch budget is $20 million,
    according to Jay Walker, chairman and CEO. And most of it is being spent on mass media:
    newspapers and radio. Print ads picture actor William Shatner. Walker said, "He's an
    engaging celebrity who helped us break through all the clutter of all the other
    advertising." The accepted wisdom is not to use mass media to promote an Internet
    company, he continued. "But we believe everybody in the U.S. is no more than one
    person away from the Internet. We want to market to everybody, and that's why we used mass
    media. Besides, he's got trillions of frequent flyer miles," Walker told CBS
    MarketWatch.
